      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Chemical insight\n\nThis dramatic enhancement is a textbook illustration of the **chelate effect**. Although each en molecule donates two nitrogen lone pairs (just like two separate NH₃ molecules), the bidentate chelate ring formation is entropically favoured: binding one en displaces more water molecules from the coordination sphere while paying only one translational-entropy penalty instead of two. The SRD-46 thermodynamic data support this — the entropy change (ΔS) for en binding is significantly more positive (+9.2 J mol⁻¹ K⁻¹ at I = 0.1 M) compared to NH₃ (+1.7 J mol⁻¹ K⁻¹), confirming that the chelate effect is largely entropy-driven in this system.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes).*",
